        <p style="color:#6b7280;margin-top:0.75rem;line-height:1.75;">Apple stops releasing macOS updates for older hardware after a certain point. When that happens, most people think their machine is done. It isn't. Mac hardware from 2012 to 2018 can often run Linux beautifully, and in many cases it'll run faster than it ever did on macOS.</p>
        <p style="color:#6b7280;margin-top:0.75rem;line-height:1.75;">I install Linux Mint Cinnamon as my go-to distro. It's stable, user-friendly, and looks familiar enough that most people pick it up quickly. Linux also has an enormous range of design and customization options. If you want it to look and feel exactly like macOS that's possible. If you want something completely different and visually striking that's possible too. The possibilities are genuinely limitless in a way that Windows and macOS simply aren't.</p>
